Operative of a mildly successful nail bar.

62
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,840
“A little bit off the top? Right!”
"Whoa!"

63
00:02:55,360 --> 00:02:56,360
Male model.

64
00:02:56,360 --> 00:02:57,980
- Really?
- I can see that.

65
00:02:57,980 --> 00:03:01,020
He also used his archery and bagpipe talents

66
00:03:01,030 --> 00:03:04,510
to play a role in a film called
‘The Thief of Baghdad.’

67
00:03:04,510 --> 00:03:06,080
- Eh?
- With bagpipes?

68
00:03:06,080 --> 00:03:07,580
With bagpipes.

69
00:03:07,580 --> 00:03:09,020
‘The Bagpipes of Baghdad’?

70
00:03:09,020 --> 00:03:11,140
Was it really ‘The Thief of Bagpipes’?

71
00:03:11,140 --> 00:03:14,900
He won second place in the military piping
competition at Aldershot Tattoo.

72
00:03:14,900 --> 00:03:17,200
- But that was cake-making...
- Was that like cakes?

73
00:03:18,680 --> 00:03:19,680
Jinx!

74
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:21,080
Are you going to ice a cake with bagpipes?

75
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:25,120
Yes, you can do five bits at a time if you
blow hard enough.

76
00:03:25,120 --> 00:03:27,590
He also represented Britain at the
World Archery Championships.

77
00:03:27,590 --> 00:03:28,590
With the sword?

78
00:03:28,590 --> 00:03:30,570
Where he also used the bagpipes.

79
00:03:30,570 --> 00:03:32,680
No, this was a longbow.

80
00:03:32,680 --> 00:03:34,370
Of course, it would be.

81
00:03:34,370 --> 00:03:36,230
The Second World War breaks out…

82
00:03:36,230 --> 00:03:38,380
And he decides not to bring the longbow because
it’s impractical.

83
00:03:38,380 --> 00:03:39,380
Wrong.

84
00:03:39,380 --> 00:03:40,380
Really?

85
00:03:40,380 --> 00:03:41,520
He brought the longbow?

86
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:42,760
“Hi, can I help?

87
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:44,540
I’ve got one of these!”

88
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:47,800
He really was going to party like it was 1399
wasn’t he?

89
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:54,420
He was with the Manchester Regiment in France
and ambushed a German patrol.

90
00:03:54,430 --> 00:03:55,860
How did he give the signal to attack?

91
00:03:55,860 --> 00:03:58,410
Did he just scream and run?

92
00:03:58,410 --> 00:03:59,710
Not this time.

93
00:03:59,710 --> 00:04:03,930
I’m going to give you the point
because, yes,

94
00:04:03,930 --> 00:04:06,900
he did that plenty of other times but not
this specific time.

95
00:04:06,900 --> 00:04:08,990
He was in command of the troops,

96
00:04:08,990 --> 00:04:10,640
how did he give the signal to attack?

97
00:04:10,640 --> 00:04:12,740
Did he have his bagpipes with him?

98
00:04:12,740 --> 00:04:15,220
A quick parp on the high notes, yeah.

99
00:04:15,220 --> 00:04:16,780
With the drone beneath.

100
00:04:16,780 --> 00:04:19,389
That’s not the skill he used here.

101
00:04:19,389 --> 00:04:20,389
Flaming arrows!

102
00:04:20,389 --> 00:04:21,709
I’m going to give you the point,

103
00:04:21,709 --> 00:04:25,159
he killed an enemy sergeant with the longbow.

104
00:04:25,159 --> 00:04:26,979
Oh boy!

105
00:04:26,979 --> 00:04:29,470
Not with the arrow, with the bow.

106
00:04:29,470 --> 00:04:32,030
Yeah, with the stringy bit first.

107
00:04:32,030 --> 00:04:33,680
Like cheese wire.

108
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:37,990
To use the technical term,
"the stringy bit of the bow".

109
00:04:37,990 --> 00:04:41,940
The last recorded person ever killed during
wartime with a longbow and arrow

110
00:04:41,940 --> 00:04:44,229
was that German sergeant.

111
00:04:44,229 --> 00:04:46,759
Now, I’ve just noticed something,

112
00:04:46,759 --> 00:04:49,490
this man seemed to have a penchant...
is that the word?

113
00:04:49,490 --> 00:04:51,710
For running into battle and screaming.

114
00:04:51,710 --> 00:04:54,259
He managed to go into several battles…

115
00:04:54,259 --> 00:04:55,650
Many battles.

116
00:04:55,650 --> 00:04:56,650
Without dying?

117
00:04:56,650 --> 00:04:57,650
Yes.

118
00:04:57,650 --> 00:04:59,980
Yeah, but with the longbow you are quite a
way back.

119
00:04:59,980 --> 00:05:04,520
Norway, 1941, landing craft on a raid on a
German garrison.

120
00:05:04,530 --> 00:05:07,289
I mean, paint me a picture.

121
00:05:07,289 --> 00:05:08,289
What…?

122
00:05:08,289 --> 00:05:09,960
I’m thinking night-time, I imagine.

123
00:05:09,960 --> 00:05:11,330
Now, you see,

124
00:05:11,330 --> 00:05:14,060
it’s the point of when he starts playing
the bagpipes.

125
00:05:14,060 --> 00:05:16,530
“Franz, vat is zat coming from over ze ocean?”

126
00:05:16,530 --> 00:05:19,349
Sorry, worst accent in the world there.

127
00:05:19,349 --> 00:05:21,740
And the wheel spins and lands on Norway!

128
00:05:21,740 --> 00:05:25,530
Would that be the Boulogne part of Norway
you’re doing there?

129
00:05:25,530 --> 00:05:28,770
Yes, it’s the German garrison out of France...

130
00:05:28,770 --> 00:05:30,850
Fair play.

131
00:05:30,850 --> 00:05:31,850
Would you do it over the ocean

132
00:05:31,850 --> 00:05:34,169
or would you wait until the landing craft
had silently approached the beach

133
00:05:34,169 --> 00:05:35,979
with the whistle of the wind through the trees

134
00:05:35,980 --> 00:05:38,320
as the clank of the metal as it hits the beach,
suddenly…

135
00:05:39,900 --> 00:05:40,999
You’re nearly right.

136
00:05:40,999 --> 00:05:44,620
Yes, he leapt forward from his position, 
playing on his bagpipes,

137
00:05:44,620 --> 00:05:46,729
before throwing a grenade
and running into battle.

138
00:05:46,729 --> 00:05:48,439
This man is a hero!

139
00:05:48,439 --> 00:05:50,419
Oh, if you’re going to do anything.

140
00:05:50,419 --> 00:05:51,970
Just the thought, just to be inside his head

141
00:05:51,970 --> 00:05:54,629
as he approached the beach with the bagpipe
ready to go

142
00:05:54,629 --> 00:05:56,560
and the grenade pin in his hand thinking,

143
00:05:56,560 --> 00:05:58,330
“Yeah, we’re going to do this.”

144
00:05:58,330 --> 00:05:59,330
Again!

145
00:05:59,330 --> 00:06:01,379
“This is my time”, for the fifteenth time.

146
00:06:01,379 --> 00:06:03,520
If that was me I’d pull the pin,
drop the bagpipe,

147
00:06:03,520 --> 00:06:07,159
and then there'd just be a parpy explosion.

148
00:06:07,159 --> 00:06:11,479
You say he threw a grenade, did it hit anything
or did he throw it by mistake?

149
00:06:11,479 --> 00:06:12,569
It’s not recorded here, I don’t know.

150
00:06:12,569 --> 00:06:14,120
What a hero.

151
00:06:14,120 --> 00:06:19,040
So we’ve had France, 1940, Norway, 1941,
where was he in 1943?

152
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:19,860
Italy.

153
00:06:19,860 --> 00:06:20,880
Correct.

154
00:06:20,880 --> 00:06:22,960
He’s got some good airmiles hasn’t he?

155
00:06:22,960 --> 00:06:24,800
Did they drop him in?

156
00:06:24,800 --> 00:06:26,499
Not sure you get airmiles
on the army’s flights.

157
00:06:26,499 --> 00:06:29,199
I’ve seen a video of a bagpiper in a parachute.

158
00:06:29,199 --> 00:06:30,199
It was…

159
00:06:30,200 --> 00:06:32,400
That was so close.

160
00:06:32,400 --> 00:06:35,840
I’m going to drink that later, go on…

161
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:37,139
It was in the ’70s.

162
00:06:37,140 --> 00:06:40,900
Basically the ‘One Show’ of the ’70s,
‘Nationwide’, did a segment,

163
00:06:40,900 --> 00:06:44,080
and I don’t know why because I’ve only
seen the clip itself.

164
00:06:44,090 --> 00:06:46,210
There’s a bagpiper, a low altitude plane,

165
00:06:46,210 --> 00:06:49,060
he’s got the parachute on one of those cords
that triggers it-

166
00:06:49,060 --> 00:06:50,060
Static lines.

167
00:06:50,060 --> 00:06:53,770
Jumps out, starts playing ‘Scotland the
Brave’ on the way down.

168
00:06:53,770 --> 00:06:55,889
It’s great because he gets in, he gets the
drone on...

169
00:06:55,889 --> 00:06:56,889
♪ Na na na-na na na na ♪

170
00:06:56,889 --> 00:06:57,889
But then it hits the ground.

171
00:06:57,889 --> 00:07:01,309
And he cannot do a landing and hold onto the
bagpipes at the same time.

172
00:07:01,309 --> 00:07:04,809
No he can't, you’ve got to flare, you’ve
got to pull down both straps and…

173
00:07:04,809 --> 00:07:06,909
If that’s the technical term, so be it.

174
00:07:06,909 --> 00:07:10,610
But all I heard was
♪ na na-na urrrk urrrrrrk ♪

175
00:07:10,610 --> 00:07:13,539
as he got dragged along
by the wind on the floor,

176
00:07:13,539 --> 00:07:15,759
the mournful parp of an emptying bagpipe.

177
00:07:15,759 --> 00:07:18,449
A mournful parp of a bagpipe!

178
00:07:18,449 --> 00:07:22,159
This, sadly, was not a parachute.

179
00:07:22,159 --> 00:07:23,639
This was a landing site.

180
00:07:23,639 --> 00:07:26,900
Was this, again, the same as Norway,
yet slightly sunnier?

181
00:07:26,900 --> 00:07:29,460
This was the same as Norway,
yet slightly more.

182
00:07:29,460 --> 00:07:30,460
Ohh…

183
00:07:30,460 --> 00:07:31,909
What hasn’t he used?

184
00:07:31,909 --> 00:07:34,180
Whoa, he has his bow as well?

185
00:07:34,180 --> 00:07:39,580
Yes, he had the broadsword, the longbow and
the bagpipes.

186
00:07:39,580 --> 00:07:40,960
And the grenade?

187
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:42,599
It doesn’t say.

188
00:07:42,599 --> 00:07:45,330
He’s like the people
you get in computer games.

189
00:07:45,330 --> 00:07:47,640
“It’s funny because you could never carry
all of these!

190
00:07:47,640 --> 00:07:49,320
“How is he carrying all of these?

191
00:07:49,320 --> 00:07:50,780
“Where did he get that from?

192
00:07:50,780 --> 00:07:52,420
“He was holding a sword a minute ago!”

193
00:07:52,420 --> 00:07:54,480
And playing the bagpipes which, again,

194
00:07:54,480 --> 00:07:56,580
is a two-handed instrument, let’s not forget.

195
00:07:56,580 --> 00:07:59,420
How fantastic would it be if he just had a
batman though?

196
00:08:01,040 --> 00:08:04,749
Going back another 50 years where you’d
just have a gentleman’s gentleman with you

197
00:08:04,749 --> 00:08:05,880
and just take him on the battlefield,

198
00:08:05,880 --> 00:08:07,979
“Broadsword if you would, Jeeves.”

199
00:08:07,979 --> 00:08:08,979
“Yes, Sir.”

200
00:08:08,980 --> 00:08:12,480
“He’s a little way off. Longbow. Thank you.

201
00:08:12,480 --> 00:08:14,039
“No, nothing’s happening.

202
00:08:14,039 --> 00:08:16,210
“Bagpipes, we’ll sound some more.”

203
00:08:16,210 --> 00:08:18,380
“Number three wood for the grenade.”

204
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:24,080
“Might I suggest the pitching wedge, Sir,
they’re awfully dug in.”

205
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:26,260
Oh, I was thinking more cricket bat.

206
00:08:26,260 --> 00:08:27,860
Pitch her up. Thock!

207
00:08:28,860 --> 00:08:29,889
Going full zombie into battle!

208
00:08:29,889 --> 00:08:33,080
I seem to recall someone saying that the effective
range of a grenade

209
00:08:33,080 --> 00:08:34,820
is further than you can throw it.

210
00:08:34,820 --> 00:08:38,370
Right, so you do need something like a bat
behind it then?

211
00:08:38,370 --> 00:08:40,780
Or you need to chuck it into somewhere and
move out.

212
00:08:40,780 --> 00:08:43,080
- You’re chucking it, I’m running away.
- I’ve got the bagpipes.

213
00:08:43,080 --> 00:08:45,380
Do you want to bat a grenade?

214
00:08:45,380 --> 00:08:47,200
Yes, I reckon I would.

215
00:08:47,200 --> 00:08:48,530
“Oh... wait, no!”

216
00:08:48,530 --> 00:08:51,820
Extra second on the detonator just for the
pitch up.

217
00:08:51,820 --> 00:08:53,720
If you miss it you’re in trouble.

218
00:08:53,720 --> 00:08:57,650
Look, I didn’t say this wasn’t one for
the courageous soldier did I?

219
00:08:57,650 --> 00:09:00,430
He infiltrated the town…

220
00:09:00,430 --> 00:09:01,430
Playing the bagpipes.

221
00:09:01,430 --> 00:09:02,690
Not they, he.

222
00:09:02,690 --> 00:09:06,940
Hang on, infiltration and this man don’t
sound like words that go together.

223
00:09:06,940 --> 00:09:09,970
He was ordered to capture a
German observation post.

224
00:09:09,970 --> 00:09:11,410
How did that go?

225
00:09:11,410 --> 00:09:13,690
Er, surprisingly well?

226
00:09:13,690 --> 00:09:16,880
Yes, I’ll give you the point, he captured
42 prisoners.

227
00:09:16,880 --> 00:09:17,880
F***!

228
00:09:20,790 --> 00:09:22,620
No one tried to shoot the bagpipes?

229
00:09:22,620 --> 00:09:26,390
I’d be honest, it’s not the first thing
you’d- well, I don’t know.

230
00:09:26,390 --> 00:09:28,330
It depends how anti-bagpipe you are.

231
00:09:28,330 --> 00:09:31,300
If I was there that would be
the first thing I’d go for.

232
00:09:31,300 --> 00:09:32,631
You’ve got three bullets, what do you shoot?

233
00:09:32,740 --> 00:09:34,580
The bagpipes three times.

234
00:09:35,840 --> 00:09:38,200
I can just see the bullet going through and,

235
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:39,820
“Ye shot my pipes.
Now I’m angry!”

236
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:42,360
He wasn’t Scottish!

237
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:44,290
I’m going to point this out.

238
00:09:44,290 --> 00:09:45,300
He wasn’t Scottish.

239
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:47,320
Yeah, but they wouldn’t know that.

240
00:09:47,320 --> 00:09:48,500
He was captured-

241
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:49,940
Yes.

242
00:09:49,940 --> 00:09:50,940
Was he?

243
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:51,940
Do you know the story there?

244
00:09:51,940 --> 00:09:55,840
I can only presume that he was captured, 
went along willingly,

245
00:09:55,840 --> 00:09:59,570
